<!-- FIRE SAFETY -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Fire Safety &amp; Dryer Vents</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why commercial dryer vent cleaning is a safety requirement, not just a performance service</h2>

    <div class="fire-block">
      <div class="f-label">🔥 NFPA Data, Dryer Fire Risk in Commercial Settings</div>
      <h3>Lint is highly flammable. Commercial dryers produce it faster than residential units.</h3>
      <p>The National Fire Protection Association documents approximately 15,000 dryer fires annually in the US, lint failure to clean is the leading factor. Residential dryers running 1–2 loads per day accumulate lint slowly. A commercial dryer in a laundromat running 18 cycles per day produces the equivalent lint accumulation of weeks of residential use in a single day. The duct runs in SoCal apartment buildings, LA mid-rise, Long Beach high-rise, OC condos, IE multi-unit residential, are often long and complex with multiple 90-degree bends through walls and floors that trap lint at each turn.</p>
      <p>The failure sequence is predictable: lint accumulates in the duct, restricts airflow, dryer overheats, thermal fuse blows. The first sign is usually slower drying times. The operator replaces the thermal fuse (or calls us to replace it), and the cycle repeats faster, because the underlying vent restriction is still there. We always inspect and recommend cleaning when we replace a thermal fuse, because a blown fuse is almost always a symptom of vent restriction, not a standalone component failure.</p>

      <div class="f-steps">
        <div class="f-step"><strong>Step 1, Slow drying</strong><span>Lint builds up, restricts airflow, dryer takes longer. Often dismissed as "just how the machine is"</span></div>
        <div class="f-step"><strong>Step 2, Overheating</strong><span>Restricted airflow causes heat to build inside the drum. Dryer runs very hot. Burning smell may appear</span></div>
        <div class="f-step"><strong>Step 3, Thermal fuse blows</strong><span>Safety device trips to prevent fire. Dryer stops producing heat. Often misdiagnosed as heating element failure</span></div>
        <div class="f-step"><strong>Step 4, Fire risk</strong><span>Without vent cleaning, the thermal fuse blows repeatedly. Eventually the safety system doesn't trigger in time</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- DIAGNOSTIC GUIDE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Before You Call: Quick Diagnostic Guide</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Check these four things first, you may save a service call</h2>

    <div class="diag-block">
      <div class="d-label">🔍 Self-Diagnostic, 5 Minutes</div>
      <h3>80% of commercial dryer "not heating" calls are vent issues. Check these before calling.</h3>
      <div class="diag-steps">
        <div class="diag-step">
          <div class="ds-num">1</div>
          <p><strong>Clean the lint screen completely.</strong> A heavily loaded lint screen alone can restrict airflow enough to cause slow drying and overheating. Remove the screen, clear all lint, and reinstall. Run a short cycle and check if performance improves.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diag-step">
          <div class="ds-num">2</div>
          <p><strong>Check the exterior vent cap.</strong> Go outside and find where your dryer vents to the exterior, typically a louvered cap on the building wall or roof. Start the dryer and check that the louvers are opening and you can feel strong airflow. A vent cap that won't open or has weak airflow confirms duct blockage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diag-step">
          <div class="ds-num">3</div>
          <p><strong>Feel the exhaust vent hose temperature.</strong> The flexible duct behind the dryer should feel warm but not hot during operation. If it's extremely hot or you can smell burning lint, stop the dryer, vent restriction is likely and the situation is a fire risk.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diag-step">
          <div class="ds-num">4</div>
          <p><strong>Note whether it's "no heat at all" or "slow/insufficient heat."</strong> True heating element or thermal fuse failure produces no heat at all, the drum tumbles but clothes come out cold. Vent restriction produces reduced or inconsistent heat, clothes are damp after a full cycle, not cold. This distinction helps us diagnose faster and bring the right equipment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose in SoCal commercial dryers</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Heating / No Heat</h3>
        <p>Electric dryers: failed heating element or blown thermal fuse (if thermal fuse, check vent before replacing, fuse will blow again). Gas dryers: failed igniter or gas valve. We check vent condition before condemning heating components, clogged vents cause thermal fuses to blow and are almost always the root cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Slow Drying / Takes Multiple Cycles</h3>
        <p>Restricted exhaust vent, the most common commercial dryer complaint across SoCal. Lint accumulates in the duct over months, restricting airflow until the dryer needs 2–3 cycles to dry a single load. Vent cleaning alone resolves this in most cases without any parts replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Overheating / Burning Smell</h3>
        <p>Restricted vent causing heat buildup inside the drum, or a failed cycling thermostat that's allowing the element to stay on beyond its normal cycle. Either way, stop using the dryer. Overheating is both a fire risk and a component damage risk, sustained overheating destroys heating elements and wiring insulation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Drum Not Turning</h3>
        <p>Broken drive belt (the most common cause, inexpensive to replace), failed drive motor, or a worn drum bearing. On coin-operated commercial dryers, the drum sees significantly higher cycle counts than residential units, drive belts are consumable parts in high-volume laundromats and need periodic replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Squealing / Grinding Noise</h3>
        <p>Drum bearing failure or worn drum glides, the felt or plastic supports that allow the drum to rotate smoothly. On commercial front-loaders, bearing failure presents as a deep grinding sound on rotation. Catch it early: a bearing replacement is much less expensive than a repair that includes drum damage from a seized bearing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Start</h3>
        <p>Door switch failure (prevents cycle from initiating), coin mechanism issues on coin-operated machines, or a control board fault. For coin-operated dryers, we assess the mechanical dryer systems, the payment mechanism itself may require the coin equipment vendor if it's a payment system electronics failure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

