<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Hollywood · 12-Machine Laundromat · Speed Queen SDGNCAGS Coin-Op Gas Dryer</div>
        <h3>"Three dryers running but not getting hot, thermal fuses keep blowing"</h3>
        <p>Three Speed Queen gas dryers with blown thermal fuses, the operator had been replacing thermal fuses himself every few weeks without addressing the root cause. The fuse protects against overheating, and in all three units, the exhaust venting was significantly restricted with compacted lint. The machines were cycling normally but heat was being trapped inside the drum, tripping the thermal protection repeatedly.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Inspected duct runs for all three dryers, found 18–24 inches of compacted lint in each duct at the first bend, plus partial restriction at the exterior vent caps on the roof. Commercial rotary brush cleaning of all three duct runs. Replaced thermal fuses and verified igniter function. All three dryers producing normal heat within spec on first cycle after cleaning. Operator had spent approximately $90 in parts over 6 weeks trying to fix the symptom; the actual repair was the vent cleaning. Enrolled in annual vent cleaning contract.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · 30-Unit Apartment Building · Huebsch HDET2RGS Stack Dryer</div>
        <h3>"Stacked dryer unit, bottom dryer works, top dryer no heat"</h3>
        <p>Failed heating element on the top dryer of a Huebsch stacked washer-dryer unit in a shared laundry room. Stacked units share a common exhaust duct in most LA apartment installations, the duct serves both dryers through a Y-junction. The bottom dryer functioned because its portion of the duct was less restricted; the top dryer's section had accumulated enough lint to cause thermal fuse and ultimately heating element failure from repeated overheating.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced heating element on top unit. Cleaned the full shared duct run from both dryer connections through to the exterior vent, found significant lint at the Y-junction. Inspected bottom dryer thermal fuse (intact but showing heat discoloration indicating it's been stressed). Monitored both units through full dry cycles. Recommended annual duct cleaning for this installation specifically, shared duct runs in stacked configurations accumulate lint at the junction faster than independent duct installations.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Anaheim (OC) · Gym / Fitness Center · Dexter T-50x2 Stack Dryer</div>
        <h3>"Dryer drum making loud grinding noise, won't run a full cycle"</h3>
        <p>Failed rear drum bearing on a Dexter stacked commercial dryer in an Anaheim gym laundry room, the bearing had been failing progressively for weeks, with staff noting increasing noise but continuing to operate the dryer. By the time we arrived, the bearing had worn enough that the drum was running out of true, creating a loud grinding and occasional thumping as the drum contacted the housing. The gym was running the towel service out of one functional dryer unit.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Disassembled drum assembly to access rear bearing. Found bearing significantly worn with inner race damage, consistent with extended operation past the bearing's failure point. Replaced rear bearing and front drum glides simultaneously (replacing both prevents the other from failing soon after). Cleaned the exhaust duct while the unit was disassembled, found moderate lint buildup. Tested through 3 dry cycles with towel loads. Full operation restored. Gym is now on a 6-month maintenance contract.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura) · 18-Unit Apartment Building · Maytag Commercial MDE25PD</div>
        <h3>"Burning smell from laundry room, tenants concerned"</h3>
        <p>Called in as an emergency by the property manager of a Thousand Oaks apartment building after multiple tenants reported a burning smell from the shared laundry room. On arrival, found one of two Maytag Commercial electric dryers running with a severely restricted exhaust duct, the exterior vent cap had partially failed, blocking the outlet. The dryer was running with almost no exhaust airflow, causing the drum interior to reach temperatures well above normal operating range. Burning lint smell was escaping around the drum seals.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Immediately stopped both dryers and inspected both duct runs. Primary dryer: replaced failed exterior vent cap, cleared compacted lint from full duct run (approximately 22 feet with two 90-degree bends). Replaced thermal fuse that had blown. Second dryer: duct was clean, no intervention needed. Verified both dryers operating with normal exhaust airflow and temperature before leaving. Property manager was visibly relieved, had been worried about a fire. No structural damage. Both units back in service within 2 hours. Installed annual maintenance contract same day.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

